It is in many ways a perfect film.

19:26.457 --> 19:29.876
<i>What is down-home Southern cooking?</i>

19:29.877 --> 19:31.711
<i>Where did it come from?</i>

19:31.712 --> 19:33.964
<i>Who's responsible?</i>

19:33.965 --> 19:37.258
<i>Well, it's always useful when
asking those kinds of questions</i>

19:37.259 --> 19:39.678
<i>wherever you are to ask, first,</i>

19:39.679 --> 19:43.056
<i>who did the cooking back then in the beginning?</i>

19:43.057 --> 19:46.184
<i>Where did they come from?</i>
When you meet people here,

19:46.185 --> 19:49.312
you know that you're seeing a

19:49.313 --> 19:50.981
direct descendant of a slave

19:50.982 --> 19:53.984
that was here after the slaves were freed.

19:53.985 --> 19:57.236
<i>Ashley Green grew up on
Mosquito Beach on James Island</i>

19:57.237 --> 19:58.488
<i>in Charleston.</i>

19:58.489 --> 20:00.032
<i>Her mother owns the property</i>

20:00.033 --> 20:03.201
<i>which has been in her family for generations.</i>

20:03.202 --> 20:06.621
<i>Fact of the matter is, in the
old South back when the dishes,</i>

20:06.622 --> 20:09.499
<i>ingredients, flavors of Southern cooking,</i>

20:09.500 --> 20:12.627
<i>which is to say American cooking
as opposed to European,</i>

20:12.628 --> 20:15.672
<i>chances are that food was grown,</i>

20:15.673 --> 20:19.719
<i>gathered, produced and prepared by African slaves.</i>

20:21.846 --> 20:25.473
<i>Chef VJ Dennis has made it a
personal mission to celebrate</i>

20:25.474 --> 20:28.935
<i>and protect the culinary
traditions his ancestors passed</i>

20:28.936 --> 20:31.063
<i>down to him.</i>

20:31.064 --> 20:33.148
This is some local blue crab.

20:33.149 --> 20:34.858
Just freshly seasoned.

20:34.859 --> 20:37.194
This is a play on some garlic crabs.

20:37.195 --> 20:40.030
This is shrimp butter instead of the garlic butter.

20:40.031 --> 20:42.741
You have the play of the French influence

20:42.742 --> 20:45.493
into the cuisine right here.

20:45.494 --> 20:48.788
<i>The flavors and textures and
food ways of West Africa</i>

20:48.789 --> 20:50.832
<i>are all over Southern cooking.</i>

20:50.833 --> 20:53.919
<i>And there are few better places
to see how short the line</i>

20:53.920 --> 20:58.464
<i>between there and here than Gullah culture.</i>

20:58.465 --> 21:00.217
I'm really enjoying this. I got to tell you.

21:00.218 --> 21:01.593
This is so delicious.

21:01.594 --> 21:03.428
Oh, my.

21:03.429 --> 21:07.515
How African is traditional Gullah cooking?

21:07.516 --> 21:09.851
I think what happens is you change the location

21:09.852 --> 21:12.854
of the people but you did not
change who the people were.

21:12.855 --> 21:16.191
You did not change the
information that they came with,

21:16.192 --> 21:18.068
with their traditions.

21:18.069 --> 21:20.987
If you look at the history of
American food, you'll quickly

21:20.988 --> 21:26.869
see this is one of the first
true cuisines of America.

21:29.538 --> 21:33.083
What's that? What is this? This looks good.

21:33.084 --> 21:34.084
West Africa...

21:34.085 --> 21:35.168
All right.

21:35.169 --> 21:37.212
<i>Soft shell crabs and konk</i>

21:37.213 --> 21:40.048
<i>in a decidedly West African peanut stew</i>

21:40.049 --> 21:45.595
<i>with Carolina rice, sautéed squash, and zucchini.</i>

21:45.596 --> 21:47.180
Oh, that's so good.

21:47.181 --> 21:51.517
It's been a while since I've had konk.

21:51.518 --> 21:53.519
Clearly, correct me if I'm wrong,

21:53.520 --> 21:55.605
there's a different kind of
interest in Charleston than

21:55.606 --> 21:57.690
existed 20 years ago.

21:57.691 --> 21:59.025
Right?

21:59.026 --> 22:00.819
Is something happening here?

22:00.820 --> 22:02.528
What's changed?

22:02.529 --> 22:07.617
It's good to have people, to
have a more diverse community in

22:07.618 --> 22:09.995
a sense, but then you also lose a little bit.

22:09.996 --> 22:12.497
The danger is they're coming to Charleston

22:12.498 --> 22:14.499
because of the beauty,

22:14.500 --> 22:18.170
and we're having to fight against bigger entities

22:18.171 --> 22:21.547
that seek to get the land so they can develop it.

22:21.548 --> 22:26.385
And so we're fighting to keep
what's been ours and so it's

22:26.386 --> 22:30.974
important for us to preserve this area.

22:30.975 --> 22:36.353
Preserve this culture for generations to come.

22:36.354 --> 22:38.482
♪

22:40.943 --> 22:42.819
<i>According to the US Government,</i>

22:42.820 --> 22:45.322
<i>almost 50% of all the children in this country</i>

22:45.323 --> 22:47.448
<i>fail to get their recommended daily allowance...</i>

22:47.449 --> 22:51.077
<i>Fast food restaurants have
discovered we like our food</i>

22:51.078 --> 22:53.121
<i>heavily salted.</i>

22:53.122 --> 22:55.623
<i>Just add water and two of your own fresh eggs.</i>

22:55.624 --> 22:58.793
<i>Because of industry's innovations in farm chemicals</i>

22:58.794 --> 22:59.836
<i>and machinery.</i>

22:59.837 --> 23:01.378
<i>Taste it.</i>

23:01.379 --> 23:03.089
<i>How did it happen,</i>

23:03.090 --> 23:05.091
<i>that we ended up with Southern food</i>

23:05.092 --> 23:09.137
being the most sort of cruelly
hijacked into this cartoonish

23:09.138 --> 23:11.597
parody of itself?

23:11.598 --> 23:15.268
<i>Modern, clean, advanced, complete meat processing.</i>

23:15.269 --> 23:20.232
I think it's a combination of
two massive cultural influences

23:20.233 --> 23:22.734
that came together at the same time.

23:22.735 --> 23:28.447
The idea of industrialization
came late to the South.

23:28.448 --> 23:32.744
When it hit, we got the first
nutrition laws in America were

23:32.745 --> 23:36.289
written in South Carolina
because everybody moved into

23:36.290 --> 23:39.209
mill villages and immediately
started eating processed food

23:39.210 --> 23:41.295
because they weren't growing their food anymore.

23:44.382 --> 23:46.216
The second thing that happened

23:46.217 --> 23:50.845
is there was a massive amount of
expertise that was lost during

23:50.846 --> 23:52.471
the Civil War.

23:52.472 --> 23:54.849
<i>A lot of the Southern revival,
the whole turnaround,</i>

23:54.850 --> 23:57.894
<i>started with this guy. Glen Roberts.</i>

23:57.895 --> 24:00.479
<i>A man who asked a simple question.</i>

24:00.480 --> 24:04.234
<i>How come grits aren't as good as they used to be?</i>

24:04.235 --> 24:07.237
<i>By starting the heirloom
grain company, Anson Mills,</i>

24:07.238 --> 24:09.864
<i>decided to do something about it.</i>

24:09.865 --> 24:14.160
Why do this? Why do something as unwanted?

24:14.161 --> 24:18.164
Meaning nobody was particularly
crying, you know, we need rice

24:18.165 --> 24:22.127
that used to taste like it did in 1837,

24:22.128 --> 24:25.880
we need grits, better grits.

24:25.881 --> 24:29.050
What called to you that you
felt compelled to answer?

24:29.051 --> 24:31.719
I'm a cuisine whore.

24:31.720 --> 24:36.975
You know, I think culture is
interactive with cuisine.

24:36.976 --> 24:39.852
As soon as you look at cuisine,
you're looking at politics,

24:39.853 --> 24:41.313
you're looking at medicine,

24:41.314 --> 24:43.273
you're looking at the advanced thinking.

24:43.274 --> 24:45.317
I'll agree with you, there's nothing more political

24:45.318 --> 24:46.359
than food.

24:46.360 --> 24:48.153
You got it.

24:48.154 --> 24:51.114
<i>Chef Mike Latta's restaurant,
Fig, was one of the first and</i>

24:51.115 --> 24:53.574
<i>most important on the Charleston scene.</i>

24:53.575 --> 24:56.202
<i>Determined to source the kind of local products</i>

24:56.203 --> 24:59.580
<i>you used to find everywhere in the low country.</i>

24:59.581 --> 25:02.875
<i>As much as I'd like to
illustrate that solid grounding</i>

25:02.876 --> 25:05.170
<i>in traditional ingredients and
preparations with my order,</i>

25:05.171 --> 25:08.173
<i>I could not resist the soft shell crabs,</i>

25:08.174 --> 25:09.715
<i>which are just in season,</i>

25:09.716 --> 25:12.135
<i>With a pasta and shaved botarga</i>

25:12.136 --> 25:15.054
<i>which frankly I'd slit my best friend's throat for.</i>

25:15.055 --> 25:16.132
Wow, that looks great. Yeah.

25:17.141 --> 25:18.183
That's beautiful.

25:18.184 --> 25:20.726
Sweet.

25:20.727 --> 25:24.105
When you had your first plate full of proper rice,

25:24.106 --> 25:26.941
is there an instinct to
bludgeon the rest of the world

25:26.942 --> 25:30.487
in an understanding of what
you'd just come to understand?

25:30.488 --> 25:34.282
I did not run up and down
the streets of Charleston.

25:34.283 --> 25:37.076
It was tough to dislodge people here,

25:37.077 --> 25:39.662
so I just went straight to San Francisco.

25:39.663 --> 25:40.830
Right.

25:40.831 --> 25:42.874
I gave away tons of product.

25:42.875 --> 25:45.669
And guess what, they went crazy.

25:47.380 --> 25:51.300
<i>Slow baked black bass, ramps
in season, and lettuces.</i>

25:54.845 --> 25:58.639
<i>And this to all things Glen is
responsible for bringing back.</i>

25:58.640 --> 26:02.060
<i>Heirloom rice and pigs, suckling asabal pig</i>

26:02.061 --> 26:05.688
<i>and Carolina gold rice.</i>

26:05.689 --> 26:08.400
Isn't that great?

26:08.401 --> 26:11.027
This is phenomenal. These peas are killer.

26:11.028 --> 26:12.778
I'm hitting the rice next.

26:12.779 --> 26:16.699
That's got the entire history
of Southern agriculture in it.

26:16.700 --> 26:18.243
Right here.

26:18.244 --> 26:19.827
Right there in that little bowl.

26:19.828 --> 26:24.123
This whole idea of having a century in a dish,

26:24.124 --> 26:28.127
none of this stuff was here 20 years ago.

26:28.128 --> 26:30.213
<i>Near the end of the Civil War,</i>

26:30.214 --> 26:32.757
<i>during General Sherman's scorched earth campaign,</i>

26:32.758 --> 26:35.510
<i>seed stores were a favored target.</i>

26:35.511 --> 26:38.930
<i>It was largely African slaves
who were able to save the seeds</i>

26:38.931 --> 26:43.935
<i>that Glen is now able to locate and reintroduce.</i>

26:43.936 --> 26:47.146
It is those people who kept the corn.

26:47.147 --> 26:49.606
It is those people who kept the cow peas.

26:49.607 --> 26:52.651
It's those people who kept the
vegetables because they couldn't

26:52.652 --> 26:54.653
buy their way out of not doing it.

26:54.654 --> 26:58.657
Will you talk about chitlins, pig foot, hog maws,

26:58.658 --> 27:00.285
African Americans in the north do not

27:00.286 --> 27:04.830
embrace those classics of the

27:04.831 --> 27:08.918
South as an overlay of pain and
oppression that goes with it.

27:08.919 --> 27:10.711
How do we combat that?

27:10.712 --> 27:13.714
What you're speaking about is
walking away from your own

27:13.715 --> 27:16.384
culinary heritage because of social sensitivity.

27:16.385 --> 27:19.678
Bottom line is, if you want
something that's compelling,

27:19.679 --> 27:24.518
that draws on your soul, this
is why they call it soul food.

27:28.606 --> 27:32.275
I need the finest in turkey-killing couture.

27:32.276 --> 27:34.693
I want to be ninja-like and I want to look cool.

27:34.694 --> 27:40.158
Camouflage is the standard go out
wearing South Carolina, so...

27:40.159 --> 27:44.787
I'm bringing that look to New York.

27:44.788 --> 27:46.205
<i>The cool, clear morning</i>

27:46.206 --> 27:48.707
<i>and I do what any sensible Charlestonian</i>

27:48.708 --> 27:50.709
<i>would do on a day like this,</i>

27:50.710 --> 27:52.253
<i>look for turkeys to kill.</i>

27:52.254 --> 27:53.338
Pants, need those.

27:53.339 --> 27:54.632
All right.

27:56.634 --> 27:59.927
You know, in South Carolina, our
state bird is the mosquito.

27:59.928 --> 28:02.096
Right. So I want to be covered head to toe.

28:02.097 --> 28:05.184
We need your face covered up.

28:07.478 --> 28:10.813
Going to the waffle house wearing this.

28:10.814 --> 28:12.732
This is totally me.

28:14.901 --> 28:16.693
We do have some turkey vests.

28:16.694 --> 28:18.363
Turkey vest, yes.

28:18.364 --> 28:20.491
I just... gotta have it.

28:25.037 --> 28:28.414
This is your last day on earth, Mr. turkey.

28:28.415 --> 28:30.625
You will die now.

28:30.626 --> 28:32.878
Prepare to meet your maker.

