30:31.789 --> 30:33.914
What's your impression of Charleston?

30:33.915 --> 30:38.169
It's one of those weird
distinctly American mutations

30:38.170 --> 30:41.255
kind of like rock 'n' roll or jazz or blues.

30:41.256 --> 30:43.424
That's what makes Charleston so
cool, though, there's really

30:43.425 --> 30:45.384
nothing else like it in America

30:45.385 --> 30:47.219
and it's been unique since the

30:47.220 --> 30:48.680
early part of the 18th century

30:48.681 --> 30:51.182
and the city works hard to preserve that.

30:51.183 --> 30:54.101
We have an incredibly gorgeous
city that people want

30:54.102 --> 30:56.604
to visit. So we have the advantage of tourism.

30:56.605 --> 31:00.191
The clientele definitely gives
us the opportunity to be

31:00.192 --> 31:02.485
this progressive or...

31:02.486 --> 31:03.611
Almost push us to be more

31:03.612 --> 31:05.070
than we can even be.

31:05.071 --> 31:07.072
We have an active cuisine.

31:07.073 --> 31:08.866
We've recovered all these

31:08.867 --> 31:12.036
ingredients and rediscovered
a lot of the agricultural

31:12.037 --> 31:16.666
influences that were destroyed
in the 20th century, but we're

31:16.667 --> 31:19.251
not just recreating history.

31:19.252 --> 31:21.629
We're not going back and cooking the Civil War.

31:21.630 --> 31:24.423
These guys are pushing the food
forward here and we're creating

31:24.424 --> 31:26.217
a new cuisine.

31:26.218 --> 31:28.970
Got to be a happy day when you
take a Cesar off the menu.

31:45.529 --> 31:50.616
We're one of the last few hunters in the world.

31:50.617 --> 31:52.993
There's no store for us to go offshore

31:52.994 --> 31:55.079
to go and pick those fish up.

31:55.080 --> 31:56.455
We have to look for them. We have to go and sort of

31:56.456 --> 31:58.957
find the ones we're allowed to harvest.

31:58.958 --> 32:02.545
We're the last of the final
frontier of hunters, you know,

32:02.546 --> 32:05.965
to go in and feed the world and that's what we do.

32:10.220 --> 32:14.056
<i>Mark Mahefka has been a fisherman since the '70s.</i>

32:14.057 --> 32:16.350
<i>He takes an unusual and much-needed approach</i>

32:16.351 --> 32:18.185
<i>to catching fish.</i>

32:18.186 --> 32:21.313
<i>Instead of raking the sea of
the same overfished mindlessly</i>

32:21.314 --> 32:23.232
<i>populous species, he</i>

32:23.233 --> 32:26.569
<i>passionately promotes the just
as good and usually better less</i>

32:26.570 --> 32:28.987
<i>known and underutilized stuff.</i>

32:28.988 --> 32:32.241
One of the great things about the
low country is the flavor of

32:32.242 --> 32:35.620
our waterways and that wasn't
being represented properly in

32:35.621 --> 32:37.538
all the restaurants.

32:37.539 --> 32:40.833
All of a sudden I hear about
this guy who has the most

32:40.834 --> 32:42.460
beautiful fish you've ever seen,

32:42.461 --> 32:46.714
but you got to go to the dock and get it.

32:46.715 --> 32:48.549
<i>Frustrated by the conventional wisdom,</i>

32:48.550 --> 32:51.135
<i>mishandling of fish by other distributors</i>

32:51.136 --> 32:54.806
<i>and the narrow range on the
market, he became his own</i>

32:54.807 --> 32:58.768
<i>dealer, starting Abundant
Seafood, one of the country's</i>

32:58.769 --> 33:03.439
<i>first community supported fisheries, CSFS.</i>

33:03.440 --> 33:05.149
<i>He's changed the way people think</i>

33:05.150 --> 33:08.653
<i>about so-called trash fish.</i>

33:08.654 --> 33:10.154
Look at how beautiful that is.

33:10.155 --> 33:12.156
<i>Today's catch: Triggerfish.</i>

33:12.157 --> 33:13.449
Any market for these things?

33:13.450 --> 33:14.450
Oh, my God.

33:14.451 --> 33:15.660
Yeah?

33:15.661 --> 33:16.661
We can't keep it in house enough.

33:16.662 --> 33:18.412
Really? -Really.

33:18.413 --> 33:22.416
The crazy thing is, like, even
five years ago there wasn't

33:22.417 --> 33:24.001
a single one of these on the menu.

33:24.002 --> 33:25.294
Before we all knew Mark,

33:25.295 --> 33:27.964
everyone had the same crap on the menu.

33:27.965 --> 33:30.090
Tuna, salmon, grouper, snapper.

33:30.091 --> 33:35.053
Which is good stuff, but as we
all know, we overfished that.

33:35.054 --> 33:39.892
Mark really taught all of us
the beauty of stuff like this.

33:39.893 --> 33:42.353
Nice.

33:42.354 --> 33:44.356
♪

33:45.440 --> 33:47.065
This is a half-shell style.

33:47.066 --> 33:48.860
You leave the scale on, the skin on.

33:48.861 --> 33:50.653
Cook it one side up.

33:50.654 --> 33:52.154
It's sort of basting itself.

33:52.155 --> 33:54.448
It makes, like, a cup.

33:54.449 --> 33:56.158
It's very creole.

33:56.159 --> 33:59.537
Is there something out there
that you're seeing that's still

33:59.538 --> 34:01.747
a hard sell that you wish people would...

34:01.748 --> 34:03.415
One of the hardest sells is amber jack.

34:03.416 --> 34:04.667
Amber jack.

34:04.668 --> 34:05.960
The Japanese love it.

34:05.961 --> 34:07.419
Amber jack.

34:07.420 --> 34:09.338
Look at that. That is pretty.

34:09.339 --> 34:11.297
Smells good. -Wow. Yum.

34:11.299 --> 34:13.051
Mmm.

34:15.679 --> 34:17.554
I could eat that all year.

34:17.556 --> 34:18.931
Charcoal and fish.

34:18.931 --> 34:20.474
I know.

34:20.475 --> 34:22.518
Damn, that's good. -Wow.

34:25.898 --> 34:28.608
♪

34:35.614 --> 34:39.911
Everybody thinks there's all

34:39.911 --> 34:41.620
this great barbecue in the South.

34:41.621 --> 34:44.706
It's 99% terrible barbecue.

34:44.708 --> 34:48.543
And so to get real barbecue, you got to drive.

34:48.545 --> 34:51.422
<i>Way out in the weeds, off the main road</i>

34:51.422 --> 34:55.009
<i>and good freaking luck if
you can find it, is one of</i>

34:55.010 --> 34:59.137
<i>the most respected barbecue joints in the US of A.</i>

34:59.138 --> 35:00.723
<i>Run by one of the most respected</i>

35:00.724 --> 35:03.475
<i>old-school pit masters.</i>

35:03.476 --> 35:04.810
<i>Ask a chef.</i>

35:04.811 --> 35:07.063
<i>Ask anybody who knows good</i>

35:07.064 --> 35:08.773
<i>barbecue and they will tell you</i>

35:08.774 --> 35:10.274
<i>where to go.</i>

35:10.275 --> 35:12.026
<i>Here.</i>

35:12.027 --> 35:15.362
<i>A rundown looking takeout
about two hours' drive out of</i>

35:15.363 --> 35:19.324
<i>Charleston in Hemingway, South Carolina.</i>

35:19.325 --> 35:20.492
Now how long have you been doing this?

35:20.493 --> 35:22.202
Since I was 11.

35:22.203 --> 35:23.287
Grew up doing this.

35:23.288 --> 35:25.039
Crazy.

35:25.040 --> 35:26.916
My family started in 1972.

35:26.917 --> 35:28.459
So I grew up running around this place.

35:28.460 --> 35:29.710
It's hard.

35:29.711 --> 35:30.962
It is.

35:30.963 --> 35:32.379
That's why no one does it, man.

35:32.380 --> 35:34.172
That's why there's nothing but bad barbecue.

35:34.173 --> 35:38.010
Because in my opinion the only
true way to make barbecue is the

35:38.011 --> 35:41.722
burn barrel and the pits and
you got to stay up all night.

35:41.723 --> 35:43.181
All night.

35:43.182 --> 35:44.935
♪

35:48.855 --> 35:52.858
<i>Rodney Scott, a man sought
after all over the world for</i>

35:52.859 --> 35:56.779
<i>some of the finest whole-hog barbecue there is.</i>

35:56.780 --> 35:59.824
<i>Rodney and his family have been doing it like</i>

35:59.825 --> 36:02.618
<i>this for 43 years.</i>

36:02.619 --> 36:05.537
<i>Burn barrel, fresh coals, slow,</i>

36:05.538 --> 36:09.708
<i>slow, slow cooked all night in the pit.</i>

36:09.709 --> 36:11.752
<i>There are no shortcuts.</i>

36:11.753 --> 36:14.797
<i>This ain't a craft. This is a calling.</i>

36:14.798 --> 36:17.175
Look at that.

36:18.051 --> 36:19.760
Yes.

36:19.761 --> 36:21.762
Oh, man.

36:21.763 --> 36:23.430
Got to have a little bit of white rib with it.

36:23.431 --> 36:25.474
Yeah.

36:25.475 --> 36:28.519
This is what everybody always
gets wrong in New York.

36:28.520 --> 36:31.313
You serve cornbread with
barbecue, which, of course,

36:31.314 --> 36:32.898
falls into crumbles.

36:32.899 --> 36:35.485
You got to have that. Look at that.

36:38.071 --> 36:41.323
This is what we call pork spaghetti.

36:41.324 --> 36:43.660
Got to have some of that.

36:46.496 --> 36:48.246
Man, that sauce is nice, too.

36:48.247 --> 36:49.790
Perfect. Right?

36:49.791 --> 36:51.167
Red pepper.

36:51.168 --> 36:52.960
That's my dad's recipe.

36:52.961 --> 36:56.672
You do not the standard South
Carolina mustard dressing

36:56.673 --> 36:58.298
at all?

36:58.299 --> 36:59.591
Pissed at me about this because

36:59.592 --> 37:01.593
people feel strongly about these things.

37:01.594 --> 37:04.262
I was not liking that mustard thing.

37:04.263 --> 37:06.348
Around here you scream mustard, they'll think it's

37:06.349 --> 37:07.850
going on a hot dog.

37:07.851 --> 37:09.226
That's the only thing they know about mustard here.

37:09.227 --> 37:10.477
Oh, good.

37:10.478 --> 37:12.771
Oh, man, that's just so good.

37:12.772 --> 37:15.983
How many hours, about, that pig is cooking?

37:15.984 --> 37:17.693
12 hours. About 12.

37:17.694 --> 37:18.986
You have to love it.

37:18.987 --> 37:20.445
You have to be head over heels

37:20.446 --> 37:22.280
in love with it to do that every day.

37:22.281 --> 37:23.824
I mean, do you ever get sick of eating barbecue?

37:23.825 --> 37:25.326
No, not yet.

37:31.750 --> 37:33.667
What are we fishing for here?

37:33.668 --> 37:38.797
Well, out here we got spot tail
bass, flounder, sea trout.

37:38.798 --> 37:41.383
Really? -Yeah.

37:41.384 --> 37:43.970
I got you.

37:46.264 --> 37:49.767
The way you fish here, throw
it out as far as you can and

37:49.768 --> 37:51.476
just leave it.

37:51.477 --> 37:53.311
Just leave it?

37:53.312 --> 37:55.231
That's the cool thing about fishing out here.

37:55.232 --> 37:59.317
I don't have to be working,
not much skill involved.

37:59.318 --> 38:04.281
So how am I doing in learning
to be a red neck department?

38:04.282 --> 38:05.449
Not wearing shoes.

38:05.450 --> 38:07.159
You're looking good.

38:07.160 --> 38:10.454
Without shoes on, a fishing
pole in your hand on a dock.

38:10.455 --> 38:12.540
That's pretty awesome.

38:21.507 --> 38:23.259
That's a different pace here, man.

38:23.260 --> 38:25.636
You know, this is the way to live.

38:25.637 --> 38:27.512
I enjoy it.

38:27.513 --> 38:28.680
Love that waffle house, man.

38:28.681 --> 38:31.475
I tell you, that was like a...

38:31.476 --> 38:33.644
I like your restaurant and all.

38:33.645 --> 38:37.564
I guess you're some kind of good
chef, but that waffle house.

38:37.565 --> 38:38.732
That is a phenomenon.

38:38.733 --> 38:40.986
It really is.

38:42.028 --> 38:44.072
♪

38:51.079 --> 38:53.330
Peanuts with whiskey.

38:53.331 --> 38:54.539
Oh, yeah?

38:54.540 --> 38:56.584
♪

39:08.263 --> 39:09.805
That's good.

39:09.806 --> 39:11.223
That is nice.

39:11.224 --> 39:13.309
It's so good.

39:13.310 --> 39:17.313
How's the visit, too, to Charleston?

39:17.314 --> 39:19.064
It's been great.

39:19.065 --> 39:20.440
This is a special place.

39:20.441 --> 39:21.692
Really is.

39:21.693 --> 39:23.485
Very unique.

39:23.486 --> 39:28.573
It's been a lot of fun to watch
the food scene here go from

39:28.574 --> 39:30.826
kind of what everybody else is doing,

39:30.827 --> 39:34.579
was doing, to doing something very singular.

39:34.580 --> 39:37.124
Very special.

39:37.125 --> 39:40.044
And when you got a tradition
and when you have traditional

39:40.045 --> 39:44.631
recipes and a story behind food
like you have here, that's a

39:44.632 --> 39:46.383
really cool thing.

39:46.384 --> 39:50.137
Well, the thing is, I'm still
discovering stuff here.

39:50.138 --> 39:51.847
I've been here 12 years.

39:51.848 --> 39:54.516
The barbecue that Rodney gave us was sick, man.

39:54.517 --> 39:58.896
He is... he is a force to be reckoned with, man.

39:58.897 --> 40:04.693
You talk about Europe, everybody
travels hours to go, or travels

40:04.694 --> 40:07.612
hours by car.

40:07.613 --> 40:10.074
It's the same thing here.
We just do it for barbecue.

40:10.075 --> 40:11.367
Got a hit?

40:11.368 --> 40:13.327
I don't know. We'll see.

40:13.328 --> 40:14.494
Yeah.

40:14.495 --> 40:15.662
You did.

40:15.663 --> 40:17.122
It bit right below the hook.

40:17.123 --> 40:18.665
Yeah.

40:18.666 --> 40:20.167
So that's an intelligent
mother [ muted ] fish, too.

40:20.168 --> 40:21.920
Big and intelligent.

40:25.298 --> 40:27.591
Hook up under the bottom lip.

40:27.592 --> 40:29.468
Ouch.

40:33.431 --> 40:36.516
Open.

40:36.517 --> 40:38.102
Oh, he got my leg.

40:38.103 --> 40:42.147
He's an eel seeking...

40:42.148 --> 40:44.401
Where you think you're going, buddy?

40:45.360 --> 40:49.071
One of those fish in the Amazon

40:49.072 --> 40:52.532
that swim up your...

40:52.533 --> 40:56.287
Nice try, buddy.

40:56.288 --> 40:58.038
♪

